        <header class="article-detail-header">
          <h1 class="article-detail-title">Understanding Unix: A Deep Dive into Its Core Principles</h1>
          <p class="article-meta">Published on <time datetime="2025-02-15">February 15, 2025</time></p>
        </header>
        <section class="article-section" id="introduction">
          <h2>Introduction</h2>
          <p>Unix has been a cornerstone of computing since its inception in the 1970s. Its design principles have shaped modern operating systems, from Linux to macOS. In this article, I’ll dive into the core principles of Unix and explore how they continue to influence software development today.</p>
        </section>
        <section class="article-section" id="unix-philosophy">
          <h2>Unix Philosophy</h2>
          <p>The Unix philosophy can be summarized in three key tenets: do one thing and do it well, keep programs simple, and use text as the universal interface. This philosophy encourages modularity and reusability, making Unix systems highly flexible.</p>
        </section>
        <section class="article-section" id="core-principles">
          <h2>Core Principles</h2>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Everything is a File</strong>: In Unix, devices, directories, and even processes are represented as files, simplifying interaction.</li>
            <li><strong>Pipes and Filters</strong>: Commands like <code>ls | grep</code> allow users to chain programs together, creating powerful workflows.</li>
            <li><strong>Small Tools</strong>: Programs like <code>cat</code>, <code>grep</code>, and <code>awk</code> are designed to be small and focused, yet composable.</li>
            <li><strong>Portability</strong>: Unix was designed to be portable across different hardware, a key reason for its longevity.</li>
          </ul>
        </section>
        <section class="article-section" id="modern-influence">
          <h2>Modern Influence</h2>
          <p>Unix’s principles are evident in modern systems. Linux, built on Unix ideas, powers most servers and cloud infrastructure. Git, a tool I use daily, follows the Unix philosophy by providing small, composable commands like <code>git add</code> and <code>git commit</code>.</p>
        </section>
        <section class="article-section" id="conclusion">
          <h2>Conclusion</h2>
          <p>Unix’s enduring legacy lies in its simplicity and flexibility. By understanding its core principles, developers can build better software that adheres to the same timeless ideas. Whether you’re a beginner or a seasoned developer, exploring Unix can deepen your appreciation for modern computing.</p>
        </section>
