        <header class="article-detail-header">
          <h1 class="article-detail-title">Git Workflows: Best Practices for Collaborative Development</h1>
          <p class="article-meta">Published on <time datetime="2025-01-10">January 10, 2025</time></p>
        </header>
        <section class="article-section" id="introduction">
          <h2>Introduction</h2>
          <p>Git is the backbone of modern version control, enabling teams to collaborate on code efficiently. However, without a proper workflow, collaboration can become chaotic. In this article, I’ll share best practices for Git workflows to streamline team development.</p>
        </section>
        <section class="article-section" id="branching-strategies">
          <h2>Branching Strategies</h2>
          <p>Effective branching strategies are key to managing codebases. Popular strategies include:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Git Flow</strong>: Uses <code>main</code> and <code>develop</code> branches, with feature branches for new work.</li>
            <li><strong>GitHub Flow</strong>: Simplifies to a single <code>main</code> branch, with feature branches for pull requests.</li>
            <li><strong>Trunk-Based Development</strong>: Developers work directly on the <code>main</code> branch with short-lived feature branches.</li>
          </ul>
        </section>
        <section class="article-section" id="pull-requests">
          <h2>Pull Requests</h2>
          <p>Pull requests (PRs) are essential for code review. Best practices include:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Keep PRs small and focused to make reviews easier.</li>
            <li>Use descriptive titles and descriptions (e.g., “Add user authentication endpoint”).</li>
            <li>Automate checks with CI/CD pipelines to catch issues early.</li>
          </ul>
        </section>
        <section class="article-section" id="team-collaboration">
          <h2>Team Collaboration</h2>
          <p>For large teams, communication is critical. Tips for better collaboration:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Establish clear branch naming conventions (e.g., <code>feature/login-page</code>).</li>
            <li>Regularly sync with the <code>main</code> branch to avoid merge conflicts.</li>
            <li>Use tools like GitHub or GitLab for discussions and tracking progress.</li>
          </ul>
        </section>
        <section class="article-section" id="conclusion">
          <h2>Conclusion</h2>
          <p>A well-defined Git workflow can make or break a team’s productivity. By adopting best practices like effective branching, thorough pull requests, and clear communication, teams can collaborate seamlessly and deliver high-quality code.</p>
        </section>
